 land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Knoll","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and German: topographic name for someone living near a hilltop, from Middle English <i>knolle</i> ‘hilltop, hillock’ (Old English <i>cnoll</i>), Middle High German <i>knol</i> ‘peak’. In some cases the English name is habitational, from one of the many places called with this word, for example Knole in Kent or Knowle in Dorset, West Midlands, and elsewhere.","German and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for a peasant or a crude, clumsy person, from Middle High German <i>knolle</i> ‘lump, clod’, German <i>Knolle</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Knowler","meanings":["English (Kent and Sussex): topographic name from Middle English <i>knowle</i> ‘knoll, hilltop’ + the locative suffix <i>-er</i>. See also   Knoll  ."]},{"name":"Kniola","meanings":["Polish (<b>Knioła</b>): adaptation of German   Knoll  ,   Knolle  ."]},{"name":"Knolle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Ernst.","German: variant of   Knoll   1."]},{"name":"Knoth","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erwin, Frieda, Georg.","German: nickname for a gnarled or crude person, from Middle High German <i>knode</i>, <i>knote</i> ‘knot’. Compare   Knoll  ,   Knorr  ."]},{"name":"Knull","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erhard, Kurt, Manfred.","German: variant of   Knoll   1."]},{"name":"Knollman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Dieter.","Americanized form of German <b>Knollmann</b>: topographic name for someone living near the summit of a hill or mountain (see   Knoll   1)."]}]},{"name":"Reginald","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Norman origin, derived from <i>Reginaldus</i>, a Latinized form of   Reynold   influenced by Latin <i>regina</